results.notes:
The Parasol mushroom. (aka Lepiota procera) It fruits in clusters in a corner of a mowed lawn every summer. Some cespitose, others single. Spore print white. Moveable ring. I also find it in a flower bed mulched with pine bark around a mature pine. IMO there is no better tasting mushroom, wild or cultivated. Cooks well sauteed in a little butter and tastes fantastic!
One discrepancy:
My specimens stain saffron to reddish when bruised. This is only mentioned for the Shaggy Parasol (Lepiota rachodes), but not for the Parasol which is confusing. But the Parasol fruits in summer, not the Shaggy which has more prominent warts. Could this be a “variety”?

results.notes:
This is my first time trying to identify but I believe this specimen to be hypholoma acutum. I found the little group growing on a decaying oak branch. The stwms were anywhere from 1.5- 5cm long and the caps 1-3cm in diameter. The stems have a veil and become bulbous at the end. The caps are a saucer shaped with a blunt tip. The gills are white and the cap is brighter yellow around the edge and starts to darken and turn into a rusty orange color and some dark brown and black spots seem to devolop on the more mature specimens cap. The caps end with some small pointed frill along the edge of the cap, cap has scales. Gills did not seem attached to stem and were tightly grouped together.

I have not been able to obtain a spore print yet, and from the feild they were carried in a tissue in a straw hat for a 2 miles . I would assume if this specimen was in fact Hypholoma acutum, that it would leave black spore traces but it did not. I also saw small light green bruising marks by the stem but that could have been surrounding moss at the time of cultivation

results.notes:
I harvested specimen C (button stage) for the purpose of looking for evidence of a partial veil. Mature specimens of A. minutula (in my experience) invariably lack any such evidence. And, in the past I have examined buttons but found no evidence of a partial veil. This is interesting because I believe that A. minutula is what ret had labeled “Amanita sp-34” within the section Amanita portion of the Amanita Studies website. Ret describes a partial veil for this species http://www.amanitaceae.org/?Amanita+sp-34 .

Photos taken by pointing the camera toward the space separating the cap margin from the stipe appear to show wispy fragments spanning this space. Sixth photo is taken through a loupe. Do these fragments constitute the remnants of a partial veil? Last two photos show mature specimens found growing within a couple feet of specimen C.

Champignons du Quebec described A. minutula as an exannulate species.

Finally, I wonder if this species may be considered as a candidate for “Amanita russuloides”?
